Abstract
Biomarkers could be useful in evaluating immune reconstitution inflammatory syndrome (IRIS). A cohort of 45 HIV-1-infected, antiretroviral treatment (ART)-naïve patients with baseline CD4 T cell counts ≤100 cells/μL who were started on ART, suppressed HIV-RNA to <50 copies/mL, and seen every 1-3 months for 1 year were retrospectively evaluated for suspected or confirmed IRIS. D-dimer, C-reactive protein (CRP), and selected autoantibodies were analyzed at baseline, 1 and 3 months
